{{ill|Kochi Gokoku Shrine|ja|高知縣護國神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kochi Gokoku Shrine|qq=}} (高知縣護國神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Kōchi, Kōchi|en|Kōchi, Kōchi|qid=Q200251|lt=Kōchi, Kōchi|1=Kōchi, Kōchi}} {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=Kōchi Gokoku Jinja Yokaren Monument |url=https://www.kamikazeimages.net/monuments/kochi-yokaren/index.htm |access-date=2023-10-22 |website=www.kamikazeimages.net}}</ref> It is a [[Beppyo Shrine]], or a shrine that is particularly notable in a certain way with a significant history to it.<ref>{{Cite web |title=別表神社とは？御朱印めぐりに参考になる「別表神社一覧」とマップ {{!}} 開運戦隊ゴシュインジャー |url=https://jinja-gosyuin.com/beppyou/ |access-date=2023-04-02 |website=jinja-gosyuin.com}}</ref> It is a [[Gokoku Shrines|Gokoku Shrine]], or a shrine dedicated to war dead.<ref name=":0" /> Such shrines were made to serve to enshrine the war dead, and they were all considered "branches" of {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|en|Yasukuni Shrine|qid=Q242803|lt=Yasukuni Shrine|1=Yasukuni Shrine}}. They were renamed from {{ill|Shōkonsha|en|Shōkonsha|qid=Q11497810|lt=Shokonsha|1=Shōkonsha}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=TAKAYAMA |first=K. PETER |date=1990 |title=Enshrinement and Persistency of Japanese Religion |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23917081 |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=527–547 |issn=0021-969X}}</ref> It is on a hill.<ref name=":0" />

It enshrines over 41,000 war dead from Kochi Prefecture who died in national crises. There is a Kochi Prefecture Gokoku Shrine Support Association.

== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines:
* 105 Tosa domain samurai who died in the Boshin War during the Eastern Expedition, including members of the {{ill|Jinshōtai|ja|迅衝隊|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinshōtai|1=Jinshōtai|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11638349}}.
* Four Great Loyalists of the Meiji Restoration: {{ill|Takechi Hanpeita|en|Takechi Hanpeita|qid=Q1074298|lt=Takechi Zuizan|1=Takechi Hanpeita}} (Takechi Hanpeita), {{ill|Sakamoto Ryōma|en|Sakamoto Ryōma|qid=Q378450|lt=Sakamoto Ryoma|1=Sakamoto Ryōma}}, {{ill|Nakaoka Shintarō|en|Nakaoka Shintarō|qid=Q3138626|lt=Nakaoka Shintaro|1=Nakaoka Shintarō}}, and {{ill|Yoshimura Torataro|ja|吉村虎太郎|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshimura Torataro|1=Yoshimura Toratarō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11413307}}.
* 11 Tosa domain samurai who died in the {{ill|Sakai incident|en|Sakai incident|qid=Q1030084|lt=Sakai Incident|1=Sakai incident}} (Keio 4).
* Tosa domain samurai and others who died in the Boshin War, Sino-Japanese War, Russo-Japanese War, and the Pacific War (Great East Asia War).
* Over 41,000 war dead from Kochi Prefecture and those with connections to the prefecture.

== History ==
In Meiji 1 (1868), the Tosa domain lord {{ill|Yamauchi Toyonori|en|Yamauchi Toyonori|qid=Q11466487|lt=Yamauchi Toyoshige|1=Yamauchi Toyonori}} held a requiem for 105 Tosa domain samurai who died during the Eastern Expedition, including members of the Jinshōtai, at the domain school {{ill|Kochi Chidokan|ja|高知致道館|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kochi Chidokan|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. To enshrine their spirits, a shrine was established at Oshima Cape on Godaisan Mountain, named Oshima Cape Shrine, and the shrine buildings were completed the following year in Meiji 2 (1869).

On May 31, Meiji 8 (1875), it was renamed {{ill|Gokoku Shrines|lt=Gokoku Shrines|lt=Shokonsha|ja|招魂社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shokonsha|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}. In Showa 14 (1939), it was renamed Kochi Prefecture Gokoku Shrine and designated a specific Gokoku Shrine. After World War II, it was no longer managed by the state due to the Religious Corporations Ordinance under the occupation, and its name reverted to Oshima Cape Shrine. In 1959 (Showa 34), due to the strong wishes of many worshippers, its name was restored to Kochi Prefecture Gokoku Shrine. On July 1, 1966 (Showa 41), it was listed as a special shrine by the Association of Shinto Shrines.

== Auxiliary Shrines ==
* Kaitaku Shrine

== Major Festivals ==
* '''Spring Grand Festival (Evening Festival)''' April 1 * '''Spring Grand Festival''' April 2 * '''Mitama Festival''' August 15
* '''Autumn Grand Festival (Evening Festival)''' November 1 * '''Autumn Grand Festival''' November 2
* '''Reisai''' every 10th, 20th, and 27th of the month
* '''Memorial Day Festival''' every morning at 7 AM

